  "source_file": "mathematically_you_should_reject_the_first_thirty (mp3cut.net).mp3",
  "full_text": "Mathematically, you should reject the first 37% of people you date. In computer science, this is called optimal stopping. Whether you are hiring an employee, buying a house, or picking a partner, you face a paradox. If you commit too early, you miss the best option. But if you explore for too long, all the good options are gone. So mathematicians map the exact probability of winning. The answer is exactly 37%. For the first 37% of your search, you do not commit to anything. You just gather data to figure out what the baseline of good actually looks like. Once you pass that 37% mark, the rule changes. You immediately lock in the very first option that is better than the best thing you saw in your calibration phase. You do not wait, you strike. It doesn't guarantee a perfect outcome, but it mathematically guarantees the highest probability of success. So if you're holding out for perfection...",
